member.summary: Defines the number of points retrieved by the Time Series data service raised by the callback. If is not set, is not set and not set, the service will retrieve the default number of rows from the latest date. If is set, the service will retrieve the maximum number of rows of data from the start date. If is set and is set, the service will retrieve the specified number of rows of data from the start date. If is set and is set, the service will retrieve the specified number of rows of data until the end date. If only is set, the service will retrieve the maximum number of rows of data until the end date. If is set, called and is not set, the service will retrieve all data in the range specified provided the number of rows returned does not exceed the maximum. By passing null as parameter, number of points will be set to default value. By passing Int.MaxValue as parameter, number of points will be set to the maximum authorized value.

member.name: F:ThomsonReuters.Desktop.SDK.DataAccess.TimeSeries.UnitFormat.None
member.summary: Indicates the display units for a fact are unknown. This will be the case for all Fields that are not floating point numbers, (i.e. dates and strings). This enumeration value will also be used for Fields that are floating point numbers if their display units are unknown.

member.name: F:ThomsonReuters.Desktop.SDK.DataAccess.TimeSeries.UnitFormat.Fraction
member.summary: Indicates a Field should be displayed in fractional units. Fraction is the denominator in these units. For example, if Fraction = 4, then the Field should be displayed in units of ¼.

member.name: F:ThomsonReuters.Desktop.SDK.DataAccess.TimeSeries.UnitFormat.Decimal
member.summary: Indicates a Field should be displayed in fractional units. Decimal is only valid if the Ric trades in decimal units. If Decimal is positive, it indicates the number of decimal points. If Decimal is negative, it indicates the power of 10 to which the Field should be displayed.
member.example: If Decimal = 3, the Ric should be displayed to 3 decimal places (trading units of 10^-3) If Decimal = 0, the Ric should be displayed in whole integers (trading unit of 10^0) If Decimal = -6, the Ric should be displayed in millions (trading units of 10^6)
